Cnst:
Consent Information:

In the context of a science education grant titled “Dissemination of Scientific Teaching through Summer Institutes” from the Howard Hughes Medical Institute, Dr. Mark Graham (Director of Evaluation and Research at the Yale Center for Scientific Teaching) and Dr. Oriana Aragon (Postdoctoral Associate in research and evaluation at the Yale Center for Scientific Teaching), are conducting this evaluation to obtain information about the efficacy of the Summer Institutes. There is no monetary remuneration for participating in this evaluation.

 

The results of this survey will be used to produce evaluation reports. The aggregated results from data collection may appear in published papers, presentations, and other products. You can decline participation in an evaluation activity at any time without penalty. Although the evaluation will not benefit you personally, we hope that our results will contribute to the improvement of science education at America’s colleges and universities.

 

All your responses will be held in confidence. Only the researchers involved in the evaluation and those responsible for research oversight will have access to the information you provide. If not anonymous, your responses will be numbered, and the code linking your number with your name will be securely stored. Though unlikely, please note that the investigator can be compelled by a court to disclose this information if the data would have value in court proceedings.

 

If you have any questions about this study, you may contact the evaluation director, Dr. Mark Graham, at mark.graham@yale.edu, (203) 432-0576 or Dr. Oriana Aragon oriana.aragon@yale.edu. If you would like to talk with someone other than the researchers to discuss problems or concerns, to discuss situations in the event that a member of the research team is not available, or to discuss your rights as a research participant, you may contact the Yale University Human Subjects Committee, Box 208010, New Haven, CT 06520-8010, (203) 785-4688, human.subjects@yale.edu. Additional information is available at http://www.yale.edu/hrpp/participants/index.html.

 

 

I have read the above information,  and agree to participate in evaluation activities.

Q2.37: Trying to coordinate multi section course taught by several different faculty requires an amazing skill in managing the group where most faculty prefer to do it their own way. So, when some faculty are giving study guides and administering exams with a selection of questions from the pool of questions students saw, running a sections that are based on active learning methods and have summative assessments with higher Bloom's taxonomy level questions, makes students wonder if they are the ones doing the work and if they have it more difficult then their roommate who is taking the same course with another professor.
Q2.39: The support I get varies. Some colleagues are supportive, while others are resentful. Not all students feel comfortable in team setting. Sometimes, the pace doesn't fit everyones style. Thus, some students in the team setting may still be confused, because they need more time to process information. These are the ones I try to identify to help them out. I could see a transformation in my classroom, from the beginning of the semester toward the end. In the beginning students are quiet and reserved, and over time they do open up and start asking questions. Also, the types of questions they are asking improve. I'm hearing less of "is this going to be on the exam" and more of "If a ____ doesn't work, will it cause ____ ".
Q6.3: reflective, self-critical, objective
Q14.6: Although I cannot state that SI changed my life by exposing me to the teaching methods I have been implementing in my classrooms, it definitely made transition easier. In addition, continued work of SI is slowly increasing the population of educators who are embracing backward design, are "flipping the classroom" and are focusing on what works better with students. The changes in society are often slow in coming. Education in most societies is an orphan that rarely gets the prime seat. Hence,one has to be patient. I am hopeful, that the trend will continue. Having engaged classroom that will be effective and not just entertaining, is difficult. It requires continued support, mentoring, time to reflect and assess. I hope that we, as a society, will persevere in this effort.

Q2.37: I have to balance amount of factual information with depth of understanding.  The tidbits we developed in the SI allow a deep understanding of a small amount of material, so I need to have a large part of the class be me explaining something for about 5 minutes, then the students asking questions and getting clarification (although as often as possible I try to get other students to try to give the answer) for 3 minutes. So this allows me to do 1 or 2 5-minute think-pair-shares per class.  The ideal structure would be a doubled class - 1 the way I now teach it, the other group problem solving.
Q2.39: After implementing think-pair-share (just 5 minutes per lecture unfortunately), I have been much happier, my teaching evaluations improved, and the student test scores improved.  Yippee!  I and my co-SI attendee taught the biology faculty the gist of SI, and several of them have also found the same benefits and happiness.

Q2.37:
-Classrooms are designed with fixed seating that just makes active engagement more challenging.  
-University infrastructure is not supportive of redesigning classrooms to fit teaching practices.
-Colleagues while supportive of my efforts to incorporate scientific teaching don't have as great of an understanding of active learning as I do since they haven't done pedagogy training.  Sometimes there is a language barrier about what is perceived as education jargon.
-Faculty are (STILL!) skeptical of active learning since they didn't learn that way themselves and haven't read the literature and say things like, "I learned fine with lecture--why can't students today just put their phones away and pay attention."
-Everyone is busy.  We need time to be able to develop these pedagogies. 
-For accreditation we're being asked to design learning outcomes and assessments; however, this is done without professional development training to understand how it supports student learning rather than as just a mandate from our administration.
-Graduate students are not receiving this type of training so that when they go out to become faculty they're not prepared to jump into a classroom and implement scientific teaching.
-My colleagues say all of the above obstacle statements--they haven't drunk any or enough kool aid.

I found your survey to be poorly designed.  I had a difficult time answering many of the questions because the survey assumes I find value in 'active learning' in the classroom and have embraced that teaching method to the exclusion of other methods.  I don't find the 'active learning' teaching method of greater value than many other teaching methods and, thus, have hardly changed how I run the classes.

I've always provided my students clear learning points and find it silly that the SI community thinks 'active learning' is the only way such can be accomplished.

I suspect that 'active learning' is a good change for poorly performing educators to transition to, because it is better to have the students teach themselves than an incompetent teacher.  In many cases, a talented educator can more efficiently use class time other ways to accomplish the same end.

Q14.6:
I believe that "second generation" research (and SI experiences) should examine more carefully the differences of best educational practices at different institutions.  Many studies come to conclusions, that I believe, do not apply to the students in my institution.  Yet, much research into educational practices tend to purport that such practices work everywhere.  Also, I think it is more realistic to present the impact/costs of educational reform (psychological, professional, content, loss of some students at the top and bottom ends).  For example, I think there should be a specific SI presentation on the depressing effect it can have on educators and students when you assess difficult objectives and deeply held misconceptions.  Data should be offered for comparison with students at similar levels, institutions, and classes. 

I am bothered that this survey did not ask at all whether educators implementing the SI lessons measured the effectiveness with their students.  This is key to scientific teaching, but it was not mentioned here at all.

Also, the implications of the survey (based on question choice) is that 100% interactive, 24/7 is the only acceptable mix.  There is a place for lecture.  Lecture can engage to students with real-world applications, stories, and projects.  It can provide careful explanation of the difficult topics that students could not arrive at on their own.  It is off-putting to faculty newly introduced to scientific teaching to pretend that this means completely throwing out old knowledge and skills.

Q14.6:
I am afraid my responses might seem puzzling, so I wanted to explain why I answered the way I did. When I attended the SI, I was already a very student-centered instructor who used many and varied methods of active learning. Designing the teachable tidbit was more an exercise in the frustration of working with people who had never used active learning before and didn't really get on board with the purpose of it, than it was of building a piece of curriculum.

Overall it was a good experience. But I also want to tell you that I think that changing one small piece of curriculum does not address the underlying "problem." That is, that lecture-centered, instructor-centered, knowledge-delivery instructors have a fundamentally different idea of their own and their students' roles in a science classroom than do people like me. I see students as co-creators of, and collaborators in working with, scientific knowledge in a classroom that is (should be) designed to introduce them to an authentic (sensu Dunabr 2000) experience of scientific enterprises - NOT just "the scientific process" (as if there IS one). It is by evaluating and fundamentally altering our roles as instructors that we learn to create meaning in our classrooms, which then drive us finding and choosing concepts and scientific practices that support working with knowledge to build meaning and to explain the natural world.

I am a DBER so I really didn't learn anything shockingly new at the SI.  I think they did a very good job of teaching and I think I would have been convinced of the benefits and started implementing new things, if I hadn't been doing them already.

Q6.3: This comment is not a new trait but rather an explanation of why I ranked the way I did. I ranked the traits based on what I think makes someone a successful scientist in today's academic community, not in the way that I think makes a scientist a special person or how I would LIKE scientists to be characterized. I think conditions and the atmosphere in funding and publishing right now extremely strongly favor scientists who are determined, single-minded, narrowly focused, aggressive, and thick-skinned and disfavors people who are introverted, shy, well-rounded, creative, empathetic, and family-oriented. I think this bleeds over into department cultures, career choices, and roles that different scientists end up playing within departments. I want science to be more open and inclusive; I try to create an inclusive environment in my intro class; it feels like a daunting or even pointless task when I feel like it doesn't matter because actual science isn't inclusive.

Q2.39:
Student learning gains (measured via pre and post assessment) continue to go up as the activities I use are refined.  
Student mastery of key concepts and learning objectives as measured on exams has gone up.  I find that I am able to push students further into more complicated material, and that they are able to apply logical thinking and their background knowledge to solve new problems.  
My evaluations have continued to go up each semester, and when I went to a flipped classroom with most of the class time devoted to active learning, I got by far the highest evaluation scores I've ever received.  
Student evaluations of what they are learning and the impact of the course structure on their learning are very favorable - they see the value of what we do in class and report that they better understand the material, what they are supposed to be learning (skills and content), their responsibilities in the course, and how to learn and apply the material better as a result of the course structure than when they are in lecture classes.

Q2.37: I think implementing active learning is a lot harder in reality. First of all, you have to have a really good active learning exercise that will do exactly what you think it will do.  Then it has to be executed smoothly such that it doesn't bog down the flow of teaching and learning in the classroom.  Many times the exercise takes longer than anticipated, which can thrown off the course schedule.  Even if you use a well-crafted tidbit made by someone else you still have to adapt it for the unique circumstances of your own course so you can't just automatically pull the tidbit off the shelf and use as is.  On the other hand, it's not as difficult or cumbersome to incorporate small changes in your instruction like not lecturing all the time and punctuating your lectures with some active engagement with and by your students.

Q14.6: The SI transformed not only the way that I teach but also the way I think about teaching. My most rewarding teaching experience in my 17 years of teaching was a course that my colleague and I designed from scratch and offered for the first time in spring 2014: Cellular and Molecular Animal Physiology. Although this course is designated as a "lecture" course, we did not give one single lecture -- the course was 100% active learning and teamwork-based. Without my experiences as first a participant and then as a facilitator at SI, I would not have had the confidence or the knowledge/skills/tools to develop a course like this one. I continue to modify and improve all of my courses each semester. In addition to the feedback I give my students, I ask for feedback from them throughout the course, thus making my teaching dynamic. My students continue to amaze me with the things they are capable of doing, and I have learned that the only way to find out what they can do is to challenge them in new and different ways.

Q14.6: It was an intense experience and not always pleasant. One issue was that participants coming in with teaching styles and methods similar to SI were not embraced - you needed to only think in the SI way. Also, data on effectiveness of SI is still a bit murky - as scientists we need to keep an objective approach. Does SI work any better than other methods? It can be different, but I'm not sure about creating better learners. How to measure effectiveness of classroom activities is problematic - i try, but still left with a feeling of, "is it really making my students better learners?" I do use Bloom's Taxonomy more though.

The Summer Institute did a excellent job describing how to bring new techniques and active learning into biology classrooms, and making making examples of learning resources available. Adapting these to my teaching style, and pitching the resources at the required level, is tricky. Unfortunately when this is not achieved, the classroom outcome is worse than giving a standard lecture. I think this is because students are very much used to a lecture format and so it is easier to give a acceptable lecture. Newer, innovative class activities that are not pitched at the correct level are received more poorly by students than a "boring" lecture. This is the major challenge I face.

Q14.6: The SI was a wonderful experience that I found transformative.  Although I already was using some of the methods that we learned in the institute, I learned how to incorporate them more effectively, I learned new valuable new approaches, I discovered other very active and successful scientists who value excellence in teaching, and I developed a closer bond to a new faculty member in my department, who was my partner for the SI.  I really felt reinvigorated to continue to evolve in my teaching both undergraduates and graduate students.  I incorporated the workshop into my professional development graduate course "Seminar in University Teaching" and it has been incredibly well-received and effective.  My ~75 student upper-level microbiology course (Pathogenic Bacteriology) is definitely more interactive now, as well as my 12-16 student upper-level laboratory course, in which the students are doing actual research (some of which will be published this Spring).  I truly appreciate the work that has gone into developing the SI and I hope it will continue to be available.

In the "what is your position" question you were not inclusive because you omitted Instructor as a possible choice.  Unfortunately this only furthers societies bias (e.g., you teach at a university you must be a professor) and diminishes the role (by neglect) that instructors play at the university and college level.

Q2.37: Implementation of Clickers:  Student frustration with clicker technical difficulties led to high anxiety that their "grade" was not being recorded,  these were pre-med students and even though it was only 5% of grade, many students were heard to say they thought this was the "worst" part of the class and it made them anxious. Others brought cameras to class to take pictures of the questions and answers because occasionally these questions were redesigned for the exam.  Students weren't then engaged in thinking and working in groups, they were only interested in getting it right.  If there was more than one correct answer, with one answer being more correct than another, the students exhibited a fair amount of antagonism.  I couldn't understand it.  This was low stakes and was designed to help them understand the material.  It made them hostile and in return it made me feel defensive.  While this was true for about 20% of the class, they were a vocal group and could sometimes "turn the tide of opinion" which in large class can turn ugly.   I am still convinced that these are good exercises because the feedback was that these questions helped them 'understand what they didn't understand' before the test.  I think it was fear.  Nobody likes to see that they really in fact don't get something.  Another 10% just didn't participate because it was in fact low stakes, and just didn't care. With a large class, clickers were really the best way to implement scientific learning exercises.  What seemed to work, was to have a mix of clicker questions - some where students had to answer on their own, and others where they worked in groups and discussed.  When we had more time to discuss the answers and questions and feedback, that helped, but then we ran out of time to cover the core material.  I kept cutting material, but couldn't seem to find a good balance.   Still looking for that sweet spot.  In a different class, implemented JIT, with on-line quizzes covering required reading, where students could get immediate feedback on how they did on quiz before lecture each day, and could keep taking each days quiz as many times as they liked before the exam.  The students loved this.  The difficulty is, I had designed those questions, and homework questions already two different ways and then couldn't come up with a really different way to phrase and "Bloom" out the exam questions.  That meant if I wanted to have a good bloom distribution, the exam had plenty of nearly identical question repeats. Ack! The difficulty here was the first exam then had an 89% mean!   I had students crying and hugging me, one started to praise me in spanish after the exam. A few colleagues were raising their eyebrows at me, I was embarrassed.  Students were all saying - oh, take physiology from Prof. So and so, this class is so easy.  So,  its a learning process - can't do it perfectly the first time around!  After that, I worked on how I did the quiz questions and homework questions, and the second exam was more respectable  and reflective of actual student learning (and the students loved me less...).
Q2.39: The previous box listed the difficulties of "back-engineering" two large science major lecture courses to become active learning.  Honestly, it was a slog and a very vocal portion of students just were not receptive.  Had I the luxury of time, and teaching assistants to completely redesign all lectures of all of those courses, I reckon it would be different.  I had been teaching those course the same way for 7 years prior to taking the SI course.  However,  I DID have the luxury, of building a brand new course using the scientific teaching principles of SI.   I LOVED IT!  I was able to cover the material without a lecture!  I did love the active environment, having groups of TAS (which I recruited from undergraduate TAs, and paid myself, via promised letters for med school).  It was invigorating!  Students really gave alot of positive feedback,  the first time I taught this course for non-majors I had an enrollment of 30 students, the second time the course was offered the enrollement shot up to 120!  This was just by word of mouth!  I utilized the Sci Amer. textbook,  built my learning goals and outcomes, then the syllabus, it just fell into place it was beautiful and I loved teaching again.  This is why it is hard for me to fill in the above. I had two diametrically opposed experienced.  One where I was able to use SI from the ground up, and another that involved back engineering really large classes for pre-meds (cell biology and physiology).  The students in the new class, really did teach each other.  It was an amazing and humbling experience.  I really got how great this experience could be.  Those two large majors classes were necessary for MCATs and so students were really upset if we did not get to "core material"  because we were engaged in active learning. If I used actively learning in the classroom - they just fought and fought. In my non-majors class they loved it!  I loved it!  I wonder if I had been able to first introduce the majors class years ago as a "new" class if thing would have been different.  Expectations were already set. When the clicker exercises when well, the majors class just erupted in discussion and people were high fiving, and questions and new content would get addressed. Their would be great energy.  Even the "sleepers" would wake up and engage.  When it worked, it was great.

Q2.37:
It can be difficult to be one of a handful of people who try to use scientific teaching methods.  Students who are accustomed to a certain kind of lecture course with a couple of multiple choice tests as the only assessments are resistant to other approaches, particularly if they think they will need to do more work.  Some students think that instructors are being lazy if they don't spend every minute lecturing.  It is not practical to change how someone else teaches, but it does affect what students expect in your classroom and in your exams.  

It is a challenge to implement some of these practices in my large enrollment classes.  I use clickers, think-pair-share and one minute papers, but I'm having a hard time getting more in-class activities going for 200 + students.  The design of the classroom does not make it easy to walk around among the students if I give them worksheets - it is a very crowded lecture hall with almost no room between the rows - so I have reluctantly concluded that worksheets/group work may not be feasible in these classes.

I would have liked more follow up help after attending the SI. Though I understand that this may be difficult to provide, it makes it much harder for novices to make changes.  Some things, like clickers, are pretty straightforward, but restructuring entire courses is hard and it would have been very helpful to have someone knowledgeable provide a little feedback, given that at many institutions there are no other resources in turn to.

I did notice a definite and positive difference in my classroom when I began using clickers and think-pair-share, and was very happy with the increased level of engagement.  That by itself is worth a lot.  But I don't know how to assess reliably how much of a difference it is making to the students' learning.  It would be nice to be able to defend these practices, given that my teaching evaluations have gone down somewhat since I implemented them.
Q2.39: I think that I am more intentional about choosing what to teach and how to teach it.  I also focus more regularly on making sure that I am making the process of science more visible to students.  Also, though I have not entirely abandoned lectures, they are not the sole method, and they are broken up into smaller units, to allow for more active learning.  Students actually do seem to like clickers and the fact that they can talk to each other to figure out answers.  They are definitely more engaged and less passive.

Q14.6: Some of your questions are hard to answer accurately (probably inevitable given the format).  For example, you ask about Bloom's taxonomy and whether the respondent had heard of it, used it etc, prior to attending the SI.  A person may not have heard of Bloom's taxonomy but may, nevertheless, have used the underlying principles before the SI.  If the answer chosen is no, it suggests that the respondent began using the principles after the SI, while in reality the only thing that changed for the respondent is knowing that it was described by Bloom.  For several such questions, it is possible that the answers chosen don't reflect what the respondent actually did before and after the SI.

Q14.6: I feel that the Summer Institute has little to do with improving science teaching but is a social science experiment.  I suspect the only important questions on this survey were the ones in the last half.  It seems extremely odd that the scholarly readings were mostly 8-10 years old and many findings had not held up with newer research.  Also, a large number of methods were presented so fast that no one could follow most of them and most of us had knowledge of most of them.  The vast amount of time was spent in poorly assigned small groups where we were supposed to generate a huge report about teaching a concept.  Our group was totally dominated by one African American female administrator that even intimidated the facilitator.  She berated me for leaving the room to handle some very important things with my husband and at work and was almost threatening to a junior faculty member form her own institution.  When I expressed concerns to the individuals from my institution that my group dumbed down the concept that was supposed to be for a junior level course to what we teach at the entry level, they all felt that the same thing happened with them.  One of the people from my institution said that they had gone out of their way in a group of physical chemists and physiologists to keep the concept simple.  This group was openly criticized for present material above the undergraduate level.  One of the staff who spent the entire conference making snide remarks about southern colleges and universities was exceptionally vocal about the level of math being to hard for biology majors.  My take away from the SI is that interactive learning in many cases as presented at the institute is a way of simplifying the level of material taught and that the dumbing down of undergraduate education is worse that I believe possible and worse than is reported in educational literature.  As I said in my exit survey, this was a total waste of my time.

Q2.39:
To be clear, as these answers apparently contradict my previous responses.  Students seem to appreaciate doing evaluating, analyzing, concluding activities in class as a way of breaking up lecture.  A subset of students do NOT appreciate having to do similar thinking, evaluting, analyzing, concluding activities in exams.  (However, some students think my exams are "fun"!).

Also, whereas my colleagues are generally supportive of anyone's efforts to incorporate higher learning skills in their own teaching, they generally have not made any changes themselves and so students get a unique experience in my class (which some students appreciate and some students do NOT appreciate).

Q14.6: The Summer Institute was a wonderful experience.  I would like the Institute to focus on helping attendees prepare materials that can be used when they return to their institution - you come to the SI to develop a backward design of a component of your course with activities and assessments.  Most of the reading should be assigned prior to the institute because it really prepares you and makes you more productive; topics should be suggested prior to the institute so that all the time can be used in production of teachable tibbits instead of deciding on a topic; time should be spent on training in developing assessments and validating them.
